>[Question]
>Solve for x: log(x^2-1)=2+log(x+1)
>
>[Difficulty]
>I have no idea where to start.
>
>[Thoughts]
>I guess I have to get rid of log first.

Hello Chao,

First, bring the two logs to the same side of the equation.  Then use the fact that

log(A/B) = log(A)-log(B).

Then exponentiate both sides, that is, 

if 

log(A) = B

then

A = e^B.

I've assumed that the base of log is e.


